        <div class="shell-explanation">
            <h2>Link Types Demo</h2>
            <p>The fun part about open web features: you can mix, and choose the tools that fit your project best.</p>
            <h4>This is a port of the <a href="https://chrome.dev/view-transitions-toolkit/navigation-types/">Navigation Type Demo</a> from Google's View Transitions Toolkit</h4>
            <p>I swapped the toolkit for the Bag's <code>@vtbag/turn-signal/link-types</code> script, which lets you annotate view transition types directly at the link level.</p>
            <p>Turns out there are several good ways to get to the same destination, each with their own flavor.</p>
            <hr>
            <h3>The Code</h3>
            <p>There is no <code>routeMap</code>, just attributes on the links to specify the view transition type for the navigation.</p>
            <pre><code>
&lt;!-- In demo.html --> 
&lt;a data-vtbag-link-types="left" href="../demo/">Home&lt;/a>
&lt;a data-vtbag-link-types="right" href="../about/">About&lt;/a>
&lt;a data-vtbag-link-types="details" href="../detail/1/">...&lt;/a>

&lt;!-- In 1.html -->
&lt;a data-vtbag-link-types="details" href="../../demo/">&larr; Back to Monsters&lt;/a>
            </code></pre>
            <p>The CSS is the same as in the original demo, only the active view transition selector is simpler.</p>
            <pre><code>{`:active-view-transition-type(left) {
    &::view-transition-group(*) { animation-duration: 0.5s; }

    &::view-transition-new(root) {
        animation-name: slide-from-right;
    }
    &::view-transition-old(root) {
        animation-name: slide-to-left;
    }
}`}</code></pre>
            <p>Same for the index / details navigation:</p>
            <pre><code>{`:active-view-transition-type(details) {
    .monster-detail img {
        view-transition-name: auto;    
        view-transition-name: attr(id type(), none);
        view-transition-class: photo;
    }

    .monster-overview img {
        view-transition-name: auto;    
        view-transition-name: attr(id type(), none);
        view-transition-class: photo;
    }
}`}
            </code></pre>
            <p>With the additional <code>view-transition-name: auto;</code> property, the demo also works in Safari.</p>
            <hr>
            <h3>Backward History Traversal</h3>
            <p>You can specify not only the view transition type for when a link is clicked, but also a type for when the link is traversed in reverse during backward history navigation.</p>
            <pre><code>data-vtbag-link-types="left / right"</code></pre>
            <p>Or even:</p>
            <pre><code>data-vtbag-link-types="left / same / right"</code></pre>
            <p>Read more in the <a href="https://vtbag.dev/tools/turn-signal/#link-types">documentation</a>.</p>
